<div class="comment-content"><b>Задал вопрос Grok</b><br /><br />What do you think about the following ideas and their consequences:Algorithmic complexity<br />Decentralized control<br />Problem of interpretation of the human behavior as a consequences of the algorithmic complexity and inductive inference (what are elementary triangles of the human behavior in the economic calculation and state control context)<br />Possibility of the markets of unlimited algorithmic complexity due to the physically preserving money.<br />Limited algorithmic complexity of any one ppl<br />Elementary triangles of the human actions like in Mises austrian economics<br /><br /><b>Ответ</b><br /><br />These ideas form a fascinating, coherent framework that bridges computational complexity theory (e.g., Kolmogorov complexity or Turing-machine limits on description/computation), inductive inference (the inherent uncertainty in generalizing from finite observations to underlying “programs”), and core Austrian economics (Mises’ praxeology and Hayek’s knowledge/spontaneous-order problems). You’re essentially arguing that human behavior and economic coordination are irreducibly complex “algorithms,” that no single agent or central authority can fully interpret or control them, and that only decentralized markets anchored in physically robust money can scale to handle unbounded complexity. I find this view largely compelling—it extends Mises’ economic calculation problem into the language of modern computer science and complexity, and it has strong predictive power for why central planning repeatedly fails while markets keep innovating.<br /><br /></div></div>
